WEBVTT

00:11.711 --> 00:14.247
(gentle music)

00:25.892 --> 00:27.727
(suspenseful music)

00:27.727 --> 00:30.430
(birds chirping)

00:57.524 --> 01:00.427
(suspenseful music)

01:36.763 --> 01:38.631
(tense, eerie music)

01:38.631 --> 01:41.334
(dramatic music)

01:42.969 --> 01:45.605
(alarm beeping)

01:57.817 --> 02:02.689
(Spencer grunts) (alarm turns off)

02:07.260 --> 02:10.263
(metallic clacking)

02:20.206 --> 02:23.042
(water splashing)

02:26.479 --> 02:29.149
(Spencer sighs)

02:39.325 --> 02:41.828
(tense music)

02:52.138 --> 02:55.074
(metallic rattling)

02:57.744 --> 03:00.580
(coffee trickling)

03:09.055 --> 03:11.891
(alcohol pouring)

03:15.261 --> 03:18.097
(gulping alcohol)

03:22.902 --> 03:25.738
(alcohol pouring)

03:30.577 --> 03:33.580
(metallic rattling)

03:46.426 --> 03:49.262
(water splashing)

03:51.698 --> 03:54.400
(motor whirring)

03:58.071 --> 04:00.740
(birds chirping)

04:00.740 --> 04:02.375
- [Spencer] Morning.

04:06.112 --> 04:09.115
- Morning was an hour ago. It's nearly lunch.

04:13.620 --> 04:14.487
- What's all this?

04:15.655 --> 04:18.658
- Well, the mayor came in for his 9:00,

04:18.725 --> 04:20.994
he wanted you to know that he waited for 20 minutes,

04:20.994 --> 04:23.730
which was 19 minutes longer than he wanted to.

04:23.763 --> 04:24.964
I told him you were sick

04:24.964 --> 04:27.433
and we would follow up to reschedule.

04:27.467 --> 04:29.068
Fish and Game called twice.

04:29.068 --> 04:31.004
Seems they need someone to draft a policy

04:31.004 --> 04:33.406
on the definition of a buck deer.

04:33.439 --> 04:35.341
You got a call from Nolan Holt this morning,

04:35.341 --> 04:38.011
and your sponsor left another message.

04:38.011 --> 04:40.113
He wants you to call him back.

04:41.180 --> 04:42.115
- What'd Nolan want?

04:42.148 --> 04:43.182
- He didn't say.

04:43.182 --> 04:45.184
It sounded important, though.

04:45.184 --> 04:46.686
- How so?

04:46.753 --> 04:48.755
- When I told him you were otherwise indisposed,

04:48.755 --> 04:53.092
he asked that you hurry every chance you get.

04:56.596 --> 04:58.931
- Call the mayor, reschedule for lunch tomorrow.

04:58.931 --> 05:00.300
- Mm-hmm. - What's the name

05:00.333 --> 05:02.168
of that seafood place he likes?

05:02.168 --> 05:03.336
- Oceaner?

05:03.369 --> 05:04.203
- That's the one.

05:05.371 --> 05:06.706
- Make sure they bring out those hush puppies.

05:06.706 --> 05:08.107
- Mm-hmm. - He likes those.

05:09.542 --> 05:11.944
After that, call Fish and Game, tell them anything

05:11.978 --> 05:13.179
with a hard antler protruding through the skin

05:13.179 --> 05:15.481
is a buck deer, same as last season

05:15.515 --> 05:17.517
and the hundreds of seasons before that.

05:18.351 --> 05:19.819
- And your sponsor?

05:21.287 --> 05:22.121
- Forget it.

05:23.022 --> 05:23.990
- [Reema] You sure?

05:25.391 --> 05:26.225
- I'm busy.

05:27.293 --> 05:28.294
- Mm-hmm.

05:29.829 --> 05:30.997
And Nolan?

05:32.965 --> 05:34.467
- I'll handle that one myself.

05:36.069 --> 05:38.571
(phone rings)

05:41.407 --> 05:43.209
You gonna get that?

05:43.209 --> 05:44.477
- You know, one of these days,

05:44.510 --> 05:46.479
that thermos is going to catch up with you.

05:48.815 --> 05:50.016
- Well, lucky for you, you'll be here

05:50.049 --> 05:51.250
to tell me I told you so.

05:52.418 --> 05:53.686
- The worst time to hear I told you so

05:53.720 --> 05:55.855
is when you ended up saying it to yourself.

05:56.723 --> 05:58.725
(phone rings)

05:58.725 --> 05:59.659
- Thanks, Reema.

06:05.064 --> 06:06.099
- [Reema] Hello? Yes.

06:08.267 --> 06:10.770
(birds chirping)

06:10.837 --> 06:13.539
(truck rumbling)

06:18.711 --> 06:21.547
(engine rumbling)

06:26.419 --> 06:29.422
(metallic clacking)

06:31.891 --> 06:34.627
(door bangs)

06:34.627 --> 06:36.095
- What's up, partner?

06:36.095 --> 06:36.929
- Hey, Nolan.

06:44.036 --> 06:46.205
So, what'd you wanna show me?

06:46.205 --> 06:48.040
What's the phone call about?

06:48.074 --> 06:49.909
- (chuckles) Check it out.

06:54.580 --> 06:55.415
Whoo-whee.

06:59.652 --> 07:03.956
- Nolan, why is there a shark in the back of your truck?

07:03.956 --> 07:05.758
- [Nolan] Isn't she a beauty?

07:05.792 --> 07:08.161
- That's not what I asked. Where'd you get this?

07:09.762 --> 07:11.931
- Went and got it in Surf City,

07:11.931 --> 07:13.633
me and my buddy were out fishing.

07:13.633 --> 07:14.734
Got 'em something big.

07:15.635 --> 07:16.636
It's crazy.

07:19.305 --> 07:20.339
- Why do you have it?

07:21.274 --> 07:22.275
- Why do I have it?

07:23.242 --> 07:25.578
Why do you think I have it, son?

07:25.578 --> 07:26.446
I'm gonna sell it.

07:27.647 --> 07:28.581
- You're going to sell it?

07:28.614 --> 07:29.982
- Yeah.

07:29.982 --> 07:32.652
You know, the teeth, jawbone.

07:34.187 --> 07:37.023
Sometimes people like to eat the fin and shit.

07:37.089 --> 07:38.791
I'll make a killing.

07:38.825 --> 07:39.659
Great.

07:39.659 --> 07:40.626
- It's fucking bloated.

07:41.494 --> 07:42.762
Are you sure it's-

07:42.795 --> 07:45.531
- Stop stirring shit, don't worry about it.

07:46.466 --> 07:47.300
- All right, all right.

07:47.300 --> 07:48.134
Cut that shit out.

07:51.137 --> 07:52.972
You gotta get this thing out of here.

07:52.972 --> 07:54.807
Take it back where it came from.

07:54.841 --> 07:55.641
- Why?

07:57.176 --> 07:59.679
- Because this is a small town, Nolan.

07:59.679 --> 08:02.448
Once word gets out, you got a dead shark near the lake?

08:02.482 --> 08:04.817
People are going to equate all this to sharks

08:04.817 --> 08:06.285
being in the water.

08:06.285 --> 08:08.187
- That don't make any sense.

08:08.187 --> 08:10.857
Everybody knows that no sharks swim in freshwater.

08:10.890 --> 08:12.391
- It's the perception, Nolan.

08:12.458 --> 08:14.660
I don't need to explain that to you. Just do what I ask.

08:14.694 --> 08:16.295
I want this thing back in Surf City today.

08:16.295 --> 08:18.231
You got it? - Goddamn, man.

08:21.701 --> 08:23.336
Well, can I keep a fin at least?

08:23.336 --> 08:24.704
- Get your ass on the road now.

08:24.704 --> 08:25.705
- A tooth? - Do it!

08:27.573 --> 08:29.242
You piss me off. - Goddamn it.

08:30.710 --> 08:32.378
I knew I shouldn't have brought it here in the first place.

08:33.880 --> 08:36.082
(truck beeping)

08:36.148 --> 08:38.417
(doors bang)

08:38.417 --> 08:41.254
(water splashing)

08:51.764 --> 08:54.367
(door bangs)

08:54.400 --> 08:56.736
- Hey! What the hell you doing?

08:56.736 --> 08:59.772
You can't just come in here unannounced, Gary.

08:59.772 --> 09:01.440
- Unannounced?

09:01.440 --> 09:02.875
I call your cell, you don't answer.

09:02.909 --> 09:04.710
Your office, no call back.

09:04.710 --> 09:07.113
I mean, seriously, do you even get my messages?

09:08.781 --> 09:11.117
Besides, you always leave key outside

09:11.183 --> 09:12.351
in case you go AWOL.

09:15.121 --> 09:17.456
- Did it ever occur to you I might just be busy?

09:19.058 --> 09:21.127
- Don't bullshit a bullshitter, man.

09:21.127 --> 09:23.629
(tense music)

09:25.064 --> 09:28.067
(metallic rattling)

09:29.869 --> 09:32.038
You were coming up on 100 days.

09:35.441 --> 09:38.945
- I had shit with work, Gary, Dottie and the kid.

09:40.913 --> 09:42.715
- And this is how you get them back?

09:43.816 --> 09:45.651
They don't have room for an addict.

09:45.718 --> 09:47.887
And from what you've told me,

09:47.920 --> 09:49.722
they've made that pretty damn clear.

09:54.460 --> 09:56.662
When's the last time you actually ate something?

10:00.399 --> 10:04.136
You know, if you keep facing in the right direction,

10:04.136 --> 10:05.805
this thing's really pretty simple,

10:06.739 --> 10:08.174
but you've gotta keep walking.

10:12.745 --> 10:13.813
- I'm trying, Gary.

10:15.348 --> 10:16.515
I should've called you.

10:19.085 --> 10:22.088
- Well, have you seen her? The kiddo?

10:24.924 --> 10:26.092
- It's been three weeks.

10:28.361 --> 10:29.528
I don't know.

10:29.595 --> 10:31.430
I drove by the house the other night.

10:34.600 --> 10:37.637
- Well, look, I'm here to help,

10:38.838 --> 10:40.272
and I'm a hell of a good listener.

10:41.807 --> 10:42.975
I'll put on some coffee.

10:46.012 --> 10:46.812
- Thanks, Gary.

10:52.284 --> 10:56.455
(line whirring) - Catching anything?

10:56.455 --> 10:57.623
- Not a damn thing.

10:59.625 --> 11:00.359
What's in it?

11:01.193 --> 11:02.028
- Coffee.

11:04.063 --> 11:06.799
(birds chirping)

11:08.134 --> 11:10.069
- Ah, shit. - You got a license

11:10.069 --> 11:10.903
to fish out here?

11:12.838 --> 11:15.007
- That's none of your damn business, Gary.

11:15.041 --> 11:16.342
(Gary laughs)

11:16.342 --> 11:18.177
Just worry about taking care of me.

11:18.177 --> 11:19.979
- That's a full-time job.

11:21.247 --> 11:22.314
- I bet it is.

11:22.348 --> 11:23.716
I appreciate you either way.

11:24.917 --> 11:27.019
- [Gary] You can do this deal, brother.

11:27.053 --> 11:28.087
One day at a time.

11:31.524 --> 11:32.925
- Did you ever slip up?

11:32.925 --> 11:35.261
- I did, several times.

11:39.565 --> 11:41.567
Hey, you know what?

11:41.567 --> 11:43.035
I wouldn't trade this way of life,

11:43.069 --> 11:45.571
and I wouldn't trade my sobriety for anything in the world.

11:49.675 --> 11:52.344
(line whirring) You'll get there.

11:52.378 --> 11:57.349
- Yeah. (somber music)

12:00.286 --> 12:03.222
(metallic rattling)

12:11.764 --> 12:14.467
(Spencer coughs)

12:20.139 --> 12:23.309
(melancholy music)

12:23.375 --> 12:26.078
(water rippling)

12:33.119 --> 12:36.088
- Oh, I shit my pants. (grunts)

12:42.962 --> 12:46.966
If he thinks I'm driving back down south,

12:46.966 --> 12:49.468
he got another thing coming. (grunts)

12:52.638 --> 12:53.439
Whoo.

12:55.174 --> 13:00.112
Man, you're a heavy son of a bitch. (sighs)

13:03.149 --> 13:06.519
Here you go, Betsy, into the water.

13:06.519 --> 13:07.753
There.

13:07.787 --> 13:12.792
(water splashing) (Nolan grunts)

13:16.462 --> 13:17.296
8:30.

13:19.331 --> 13:20.166
Here.

13:22.001 --> 13:22.835
There.

13:24.170 --> 13:27.940
(tense music) (plane engines whirring)

13:27.940 --> 13:30.609
(Nolan humming)

13:41.854 --> 13:43.489
(water splashing)

13:43.522 --> 13:46.025
(tense music)

13:56.669 --> 14:00.339
(tense, eerie music)

14:00.339 --> 14:03.042
(birds chirping)

14:08.047 --> 14:11.250
(water splashing)

14:11.317 --> 14:13.719
(seagulls cawing)

14:13.719 --> 14:17.256
(eerie, suspenseful music)

14:21.227 --> 14:25.231
(creatures warbling underwater)

14:26.899 --> 14:29.401
(tense music)

14:31.437 --> 14:34.540
(suspenseful, eerie music)

14:34.573 --> 14:36.675
(woman yells) (dramatic music)

14:36.675 --> 14:38.210
(woman screaming)

14:38.244 --> 14:41.080
(water splashing)

14:45.784 --> 14:48.287
(tense music)

14:51.056 --> 14:54.059
(crickets chirping)

14:57.863 --> 15:00.566
(birds chirping)

15:02.768 --> 15:03.769
(Reema clears throat)

15:03.769 --> 15:05.704
- It's just coffee today, Reema.

15:05.704 --> 15:07.206
Lunch with the mayor went well.

15:09.041 --> 15:10.376
What's that look? What?

15:10.409 --> 15:11.377
What?

15:11.377 --> 15:13.078
- The sheriff's here to see you.

15:14.780 --> 15:15.614
- Send him in.

15:18.150 --> 15:18.984
- [Reema] Oh.

15:25.424 --> 15:26.325
- [Spencer] Wilson.

15:27.993 --> 15:28.827
- Spencer.

15:30.262 --> 15:31.263
- What can I do for?

15:32.598 --> 15:34.733
- [Sheriff] You hadn't heard?

15:34.733 --> 15:35.834
- [Spencer] Heard what?

15:36.769 --> 15:38.270
- Got a dead girl on the lake.

15:42.975 --> 15:43.909
- Where's the body?

15:45.144 --> 15:48.280
- What's left of it, coroner's office.

15:49.481 --> 15:50.983
There's a bunch of boats in the water

15:50.983 --> 15:52.618
a couple of miles up the coast from where we found the girl,

15:52.651 --> 15:54.954
I sent a couple of my guys up there to bring them in.

15:56.121 --> 15:56.956
- What'd you tell them?

15:56.956 --> 15:58.123
- Lake water tests.

15:59.325 --> 16:00.426
Figure that'd give us some time to figure out

16:00.426 --> 16:01.593
what we're going to say.

16:02.861 --> 16:04.129
- We?

16:04.163 --> 16:06.999
- We hadn't had a murder in this town in 60 years

16:06.999 --> 16:10.102
and now, in a goddamn election year?

16:10.102 --> 16:10.970
You're the warden.

16:12.004 --> 16:13.839
I deal with criminals.

16:13.839 --> 16:15.040
You deal with animals.

16:16.508 --> 16:19.044
- Well, Sheriff, I think I deal with more criminals

16:19.111 --> 16:20.646
in this town than you do.

16:22.848 --> 16:24.350
What makes you think it's an animal?

16:24.350 --> 16:27.686
(Sheriff Wilson scoffs)

16:29.021 --> 16:31.523
(tense music)

16:36.462 --> 16:39.164
- They pulled that out of the middle of her back,

16:39.198 --> 16:41.000
lodged into her spine.

16:41.000 --> 16:42.534
Yeah, that's a shark tooth.

16:45.871 --> 16:47.072
- Impossible.

16:47.072 --> 16:48.340
- Listen, I don't wanna cause a panic

16:48.374 --> 16:50.075
in town with the locals.

16:50.075 --> 16:51.310
Word gets out we got a shark in the lake,

16:51.343 --> 16:53.212
you can forget all about tourists.

16:55.314 --> 16:57.850
- Sheriff, if there were a shark in these waters,

16:57.883 --> 17:00.819
as rare as that would be, the chances of attacking

17:00.819 --> 17:04.056
and killing a swimmer like that doesn't add up.

17:05.057 --> 17:06.658
They don't come into freshwater.

17:07.559 --> 17:08.727
We don't have reefs.

17:09.661 --> 17:10.829
Slaughterhouses? No.

17:12.031 --> 17:14.199
Nothing here to keep them interested.

17:14.233 --> 17:15.501
- All right, then.

17:18.237 --> 17:19.071
Game warden,

17:22.574 --> 17:24.743
how'd a shark end up in my lake?

17:24.743 --> 17:25.611
- [Spencer] Nolan!

17:28.914 --> 17:29.848
- Warden?

17:29.848 --> 17:31.350
- Warden, my ass. What'd you do?

17:32.251 --> 17:33.685
- About what?

17:33.685 --> 17:35.254
- The other day, a little package in the back

17:35.254 --> 17:37.589
of your truck, what did you do?

17:37.623 --> 17:39.625
- Shit, man, I didn't know you meant it.

17:41.627 --> 17:43.062
- What'd you do with it, Nolan?

17:44.363 --> 17:46.098
- I dumped it by the lake.

17:46.098 --> 17:47.266
By the campground. Why?

17:48.300 --> 17:49.401
- You dumped it in the lake.

17:49.435 --> 17:50.702
- Yeah.

17:50.702 --> 17:52.371
I'm sorry, I just didn't wanna make another trip.

17:52.404 --> 17:53.238
That's all.

17:54.907 --> 17:55.741
Damn.

17:56.642 --> 17:58.577
- You told me it was dead, Nolan.

17:58.610 --> 17:59.445
You swore to me.

17:59.445 --> 18:00.446
- It was dead.

18:00.446 --> 18:01.980
I even poked it with a stick.

18:02.047 --> 18:02.881
You saw it.

18:05.317 --> 18:08.153
Wait.

18:08.220 --> 18:10.422
What you trying to say here, huh?

18:10.456 --> 18:11.890
- A young girl's dead, Nolan.

18:13.492 --> 18:14.760
- Huh?

18:14.793 --> 18:15.594
- The shark was alive when you put it back-

18:15.594 --> 18:17.396
- There's no way.

18:17.396 --> 18:19.498
It didn't move for 10 hours.

18:19.498 --> 18:21.166
- What about the one inside it, hmm?

18:21.166 --> 18:23.001
I told you it looked fucking bloated.

18:23.068 --> 18:24.603
- Get the fuck outta here, man.

18:24.636 --> 18:25.804
You telling me it was knocked up?

18:25.804 --> 18:27.139
- You got a better suggestion?

18:27.139 --> 18:29.641
(tense music)

18:34.279 --> 18:36.115
- What you want me to do?

18:36.115 --> 18:37.516
I mean, I didn't do anything.

18:39.118 --> 18:39.952
I mean...

18:40.986 --> 18:41.920
I didn't do anything, man.

18:41.920 --> 18:44.189
You saw it was dead. You saw it.

18:44.189 --> 18:46.024
I poked it with a stick. You saw it, man.

18:46.091 --> 18:47.426
Right?

18:47.426 --> 18:48.927
- Save it for the sheriff, Nolan.

18:57.703 --> 18:59.204
- It was dead.

18:59.271 --> 19:00.439
I poked it with a stick.

19:04.209 --> 19:05.210
Right, with a stick.

19:08.614 --> 19:11.450
(sighs) I need a beer.

19:11.450 --> 19:12.718
(birds chirping)

19:12.718 --> 19:16.021
(water warbling)

19:16.021 --> 19:18.524
(eerie music)

19:30.836 --> 19:33.539
(truck rumbling)

19:58.730 --> 20:00.232
- So do you even have to go to the academy

20:00.265 --> 20:01.600
to be a game warden?

20:05.837 --> 20:08.006
- About 31 weeks, asshole.

20:08.040 --> 20:09.007
- Hmm.

20:11.076 --> 20:13.745
(door creaking)

20:15.047 --> 20:16.215
- Right on time, fellas.

20:18.083 --> 20:19.918
We're in the middle of my lunch hour.

20:21.753 --> 20:26.758
So. (crunching)

20:27.926 --> 20:30.295
At first, I thought that a shark in lake water

20:30.362 --> 20:33.699
didn't make any sense, but I did my research.

20:33.699 --> 20:36.868
Come to find out, it's not as uncommon as you might think.

20:38.370 --> 20:43.041
Louisiana, Mississippi, even parts of the Texas coast,

20:43.942 --> 20:45.444
but never this far up, though.

20:45.444 --> 20:46.245
- Is it dead?

20:47.446 --> 20:48.914
- Excuse me?

20:48.947 --> 20:50.716
- [Sheriff] The shark. Is it dead?

20:51.783 --> 20:54.152
- Hmm. Which one?

20:54.219 --> 20:55.721
- Whoa, whoa, whoa.

20:55.754 --> 20:56.922
What do you mean, which one?

20:58.257 --> 20:59.057
- Look here.

21:02.427 --> 21:04.730
You see the bite ratio here on her lower back?

21:06.131 --> 21:08.333
I called a friend of mine down at the Ocean Institute

21:08.400 --> 21:10.636
and I had them take a look at the measurements.

21:11.803 --> 21:13.472
Come to find out those teeth markings

21:14.506 --> 21:15.974
are from a younger shark.

21:15.974 --> 21:17.909
You know the tooth you found in her back?

21:17.943 --> 21:20.279
It broke off like that because the shark's jawline

21:20.312 --> 21:23.248
is still developing. (crunching)

21:25.317 --> 21:27.686
- What am I supposed to tell that girl's family?

21:27.753 --> 21:28.920
- Nevermind that.

21:28.954 --> 21:30.622
So what you're saying is not one,

21:30.622 --> 21:32.624
but two sharks in our lake?

21:32.658 --> 21:35.661
- Well, unless this adolescent shark got lost at sea,

21:35.661 --> 21:38.096
I can almost bet the mama shark's out there with him.

21:39.331 --> 21:40.499
- Son of a bitch.

21:42.134 --> 21:44.469
- Look, gentlemen, you're interrupting my lunch,

21:44.469 --> 21:46.471
and at the end of the day, I need to be honest

21:46.505 --> 21:47.839
with my cause of death here.

21:50.175 --> 21:52.311
This girl was killed by a shark attack.

21:52.311 --> 21:54.846
And how that happened, that's your jobs to figure out.

21:56.048 --> 21:57.049
- How long can we keep this quiet?

21:57.115 --> 21:59.985
- A few days, if we're lucky.

22:00.018 --> 22:01.520
- This friend of yours at the Institute,

22:01.520 --> 22:03.855
you have his number, in case I have any questions?

22:08.527 --> 22:11.129
- Right there. (crunches)

22:14.866 --> 22:15.701
Good luck.

22:17.302 --> 22:20.205
(people chattering)

22:20.205 --> 22:22.040
- No, no, no, that's not what I said.

22:23.709 --> 22:24.843
No, what I said was I didn't wanna

22:24.876 --> 22:26.511
make a comment at this time,

22:26.511 --> 22:28.347
and legally that's all you can print.

22:29.548 --> 22:30.749
Harry, hold on a second.

22:30.749 --> 22:32.250
Hey, you got the mayor on the line?

22:34.186 --> 22:35.420
Harry, yeah, it's the mayor's office.

22:35.420 --> 22:36.521
I gotta call you back.

22:36.555 --> 22:38.256
Don't print anything. You hear me?

22:41.093 --> 22:41.927
Mr. Mayor.

22:43.395 --> 22:44.229
Yes, sir.

22:45.731 --> 22:49.668
Yes, sir, I have a call into the Ocean Institute as well.

22:49.701 --> 22:50.502
When?

22:51.937 --> 22:53.205
All right.

22:53.238 --> 22:54.373
I should be getting a call any minute now.

22:54.373 --> 22:55.374
Reema.

22:55.374 --> 22:56.942
Reema!

22:56.942 --> 22:58.744
That the (indistinct) guy from Port Aransas?

22:58.744 --> 22:59.544
- Line 2.

23:00.412 --> 23:01.913
- Mr. Mayor?

23:01.913 --> 23:04.950
Yes, my assistant just let me know our guy's on hold.

23:05.016 --> 23:06.218
Will do. You got my word.

23:07.953 --> 23:11.590
If you could keep the paper off my back, I'd appreciate it

23:11.590 --> 23:13.258
till we figure this whole thing out.

23:14.126 --> 23:15.627
Yes, sir. Talk to you soon.

23:16.762 --> 23:19.431
What line's the guy from Port A?

23:19.431 --> 23:20.599
- Line 2.

23:23.101 --> 23:24.936
- Goddamn it, there's nobody there.

23:24.936 --> 23:25.804
- Well, he hung up.

23:25.871 --> 23:26.772
Should I call him back?

23:26.772 --> 23:28.273
- Yeah. Right now, please.

23:31.209 --> 23:32.878
If the paper calls back, tell Harry to call

23:32.878 --> 23:35.113
the mayor's office. If he wants a statement, okay?

23:35.113 --> 23:35.947
- Okay.

23:37.315 --> 23:38.483
(phone buzzes) - Goddamn it.

23:39.951 --> 23:42.120
Gary, now's not a good time, my friend.

23:49.227 --> 23:50.061
Yeah.

23:50.061 --> 23:51.263
Yeah, no, it's not that.

23:51.296 --> 23:52.497
I appreciate you checking in on me.

23:52.497 --> 23:53.832
I just got a lot going on at work right now

23:53.832 --> 23:55.133
and I gotta call you back.

23:57.836 --> 23:58.637
This is Timms.

24:00.105 --> 24:02.107
Yes, yes, thank you for calling me back so quickly.

24:04.910 --> 24:07.245
Great, so you understand our situation up here.

24:10.015 --> 24:11.183
Okay. Wait, wait.

24:11.249 --> 24:12.484
Say that last part again.

24:17.522 --> 24:19.324
How could you possibly know all that?

24:21.426 --> 24:22.861
All right, I'll be there tonight.

24:22.861 --> 24:23.695
Thank you.

24:25.263 --> 24:26.932
- Nolan Holt is on line 1.

24:28.366 --> 24:30.168
- Go fuck yourself, Nolan.

24:30.168 --> 24:31.703
- Now was that necessary?

24:34.473 --> 24:36.174
Where do you think you're going?

24:36.174 --> 24:38.343
- Port Aransas. - Now?

24:38.376 --> 24:39.811
That's a seven hour drive.

24:41.213 --> 24:42.047
- It's important.

24:43.515 --> 24:46.151
Have the sheriff meet me at the north dock at 7:00 AM.

24:46.151 --> 24:47.853
Anybody else calls, send them to the mayor's office

24:47.853 --> 24:50.322
till I get back and keep your cell phone on.

24:50.355 --> 24:53.058
- Are you gonna tell me what the hell is going on here?

24:55.827 --> 24:56.661
- Not right now.

24:58.797 --> 25:00.131
(Reema sighs)

25:00.131 --> 25:05.036
(eerie music) (water warbling)

25:11.810 --> 25:13.512
How the hell's everybody have a key to this place?

25:13.545 --> 25:17.382
- 'Cause you're not answering your phone.

25:17.382 --> 25:18.583
- Got a lot going on.

25:20.652 --> 25:21.653
- I can see that.

25:24.890 --> 25:25.891
- It's not like that.

25:25.891 --> 25:26.725
- Okay.

25:32.664 --> 25:33.498
- What's this?

25:34.399 --> 25:36.167
- You know what it is, Spencer.

25:36.201 --> 25:39.104
(melancholy music)

25:44.109 --> 25:45.243
- I'm not signing that.

25:46.411 --> 25:48.613
- You don't really have a choice.

25:51.249 --> 25:54.786
- You come into my house with divorce papers

25:56.054 --> 25:56.955
and you won't even let me see him?

25:56.955 --> 25:59.791
- And whose fault is that?

25:59.858 --> 26:01.793
You remember your little episode at the courthouse.

26:01.793 --> 26:02.961
- He's my son, too.

26:05.463 --> 26:09.467
And you, you are holding him hostage from me.

26:09.467 --> 26:11.469
- (sighs) How dare you?

26:12.704 --> 26:14.773
I have done nothing but give you chances

26:14.773 --> 26:16.441
to have some sort of relationship with him

26:16.474 --> 26:19.978
and you've done nothing but shit all over it.

26:20.045 --> 26:22.948
How many times have you shown up drunk or hungover?

26:22.948 --> 26:24.883
How many times can you cancel on him

26:24.916 --> 26:27.285
before he starts to think you don't give a shit?

26:30.488 --> 26:35.060
(sighs) Just don't put that on me.

26:37.662 --> 26:38.563
- All right, fine.

26:41.333 --> 26:43.168
But I'm not signing this, not yet.

26:44.469 --> 26:45.804
You are still my wife.

26:47.339 --> 26:48.273
We're gonna work through all of this.

26:48.306 --> 26:49.808
We're gonna be a family again.

26:51.276 --> 26:54.946
(melancholy music)

26:54.946 --> 26:58.850
- When you were young, I loved who you were.

27:01.152 --> 27:03.321
Now, I don't know this guy.

27:06.758 --> 27:07.592
And that,

27:09.628 --> 27:11.296
that hurts the worst.

27:15.200 --> 27:16.368
Sign the papers.

27:17.535 --> 27:19.371
It's what's best for all three of us.

27:21.973 --> 27:22.974
Enjoy your drink.

27:24.209 --> 27:25.377
- It's not what's best.

27:28.513 --> 27:29.948
Can we talk about this?

27:31.983 --> 27:34.486
(door closes)

27:37.989 --> 27:40.692
(paper rustling)

27:43.161 --> 27:46.197
(Spencer gulping)

27:46.197 --> 27:47.532
Goddamn it, Spencer.

27:53.538 --> 27:55.974
(man grunts)

27:57.509 --> 28:00.011
(can popping)

28:06.418 --> 28:09.254
(water splashing)

28:23.935 --> 28:28.773
- (laughs) That's a good one right there.

28:36.381 --> 28:39.918
(insect buzzing)

28:39.918 --> 28:42.420
(tense music)

28:43.722 --> 28:46.458
(water gurgling)

28:52.597 --> 28:55.433
(water splashing)

28:56.601 --> 28:58.203
(music intensifies)

28:58.203 --> 29:03.108
(dramatic music) (water splashing)

29:04.442 --> 29:09.447
(man gurgling) (water splashing)

29:10.782 --> 29:13.284
(tense music)

29:16.454 --> 29:19.224
(water warbling)

29:22.627 --> 29:25.463
(water splashing)

29:28.133 --> 29:31.069
(melancholy music)

29:33.471 --> 29:36.808
(truck rumbling)

29:36.808 --> 29:39.144
(seagulls cawing)

29:39.144 --> 29:41.646
(tense music)

29:50.121 --> 29:52.857
- Frankfort, Michigan three years ago,

29:54.292 --> 29:56.528
and that's not the first one I've heard about in freshwater.

29:58.830 --> 29:59.831
I know.

29:59.831 --> 30:01.332
The chances of winning a lottery

30:01.332 --> 30:04.335
or a meteorite falling from the sky

30:04.335 --> 30:07.038
seem more likely than finding a shark in the Great Lakes,

30:07.038 --> 30:09.707
but there are more than 100 eyewitness accounts

30:09.707 --> 30:11.442
of sharks swimming up the Mississippi

30:11.476 --> 30:12.811
as far up as Illinois.

30:16.014 --> 30:18.817
Given the distance between the Gulf of Mexico

30:20.285 --> 30:22.220
and Lake Michigan, I have to suggest that if a shark

30:22.220 --> 30:25.123
with an extreme case of wanderlust could make it

30:25.156 --> 30:27.225
up to the Illinois River, it could surely make it

30:27.225 --> 30:29.661
a third of the way and end up in your backyard.

30:31.462 --> 30:35.967
See, the unique trick is that bull sharks have kidneys

30:35.967 --> 30:38.336
that recycle the salt vital to the animal cells.

30:39.704 --> 30:42.173
Normally, a different freshwater would dilute the salt,

30:42.173 --> 30:44.242
causing the cells to rupture, kill it.

30:46.177 --> 30:47.045
Not the bull shark.

30:48.880 --> 30:49.714
- [Spencer] Great.

30:53.852 --> 30:55.019
- I see this a lot.

30:56.554 --> 30:59.691
When people read magazine articles on shark attacks,

30:59.691 --> 31:02.894
or they turn on the History Channel for one week a year,

31:02.894 --> 31:06.164
suddenly, everyone becomes an expert, but Warden,

31:06.197 --> 31:10.235
Texas, Michigan, Mississippi, the Amazon.

31:13.571 --> 31:16.241
When Hamlin called me, I took a look at what she had.

31:19.911 --> 31:20.712
See this?

31:22.113 --> 31:24.782
The size and depth of these wounds matches that

31:24.782 --> 31:27.285
of only one species.

31:27.352 --> 31:32.023
This isn't a trick of the sun or waves or too much alcohol.

31:32.056 --> 31:34.259
What you're dealing with is a shark,

31:34.259 --> 31:36.527
and from the looks of it, a hungry one.

31:41.232 --> 31:42.600
Now there is some good news.

31:44.369 --> 31:47.538
With the lack of any salt water or appropriate food,

31:47.572 --> 31:50.241
and with the colder temperatures coming,

31:50.275 --> 31:52.110
I think this shark problem

31:52.110 --> 31:53.945
is not gonna last you too much longer.

31:57.148 --> 31:59.817
As long as you've closed the lake, I think the shark thing

31:59.817 --> 32:01.953
is gonna go away pretty quickly.

32:06.624 --> 32:09.160
You did close the lake, right?

32:09.227 --> 32:14.232
(tense music) (water splashing)

32:17.068 --> 32:19.771
(engine revving)

32:24.008 --> 32:29.013
(fishing rod clicking) (birds chirping)

32:33.251 --> 32:36.087
(water splashing)

32:43.628 --> 32:46.130
(tense music)

32:48.099 --> 32:50.835
(paper rustling)

32:55.873 --> 32:57.175
Mr. Mayor.

32:57.175 --> 32:59.310
- Mr. Harper, glad I could catch you.

32:59.344 --> 33:00.211
Is this a bad time?

33:02.714 --> 33:03.648
- Who's this?

33:05.183 --> 33:07.518
- She's with me. Legal counsel.

33:08.519 --> 33:09.354
May I?

33:17.862 --> 33:20.198
About this problem, this little problem we've got

33:20.198 --> 33:23.701
with our lake up north, Coroner Hamlin,

33:25.169 --> 33:27.872
she was up here to speak with you, was she not?

33:30.708 --> 33:31.542
- She did.

33:32.877 --> 33:35.346
- And the game warden, he came down here

33:35.346 --> 33:36.347
and paid you a visit.

33:38.216 --> 33:39.550
- That's right.

33:39.550 --> 33:41.519
He left just about an hour ago.

33:42.587 --> 33:44.655
Look, Mr. Mayor, whatever you wanna know,

33:44.689 --> 33:47.258
I can assure you that I've briefed your game warden.

33:51.729 --> 33:53.564
- You know what? I love to fish.

33:53.598 --> 33:56.267
I once caught a marlin off the Florida Keys.

33:57.435 --> 33:59.771
Came in at eight feet long, 200 pounds.

33:59.771 --> 34:02.607
Took me two hours to reel him in.

34:04.075 --> 34:07.245
Now I know you told Spencer we got a shark in our waters.

34:08.413 --> 34:11.582
Personally, if it was the family of marlins

34:11.582 --> 34:14.352
that wanted to populate the lake, I'd say, bring them on.

34:14.385 --> 34:15.553
I want a rematch.

34:15.553 --> 34:17.555
- But we're not talking about marlins.

34:17.555 --> 34:18.956
That would be impossible.

34:18.956 --> 34:20.591
We're talking about a shark.

34:26.097 --> 34:27.632
- A bull shark.

34:27.632 --> 34:29.200
- That's right.

34:29.233 --> 34:31.369
I've given the game warden the report.

34:31.369 --> 34:34.872
Amputated arms and legs, the bites aren't hard to find.

34:37.275 --> 34:38.276
Take a look at this.

34:44.315 --> 34:45.950
(tense music) - Whoo!

34:45.950 --> 34:47.452
- This is six months ago,

34:47.452 --> 34:49.620
three states north of where you are.

34:51.656 --> 34:53.724
- Watch out, watch out. - Whoa, hold on.

34:55.460 --> 34:57.895
- Whoo. - Watch out.

34:57.929 --> 35:00.231
- Whoo. My gosh.

35:03.768 --> 35:05.770
Hold on to that thing.

35:05.803 --> 35:08.339
Whoo! - Bail some water here.

35:08.339 --> 35:09.173
- Oh my gosh.

35:10.975 --> 35:13.811
Look at his paw, look at his paw, oh my gosh.

35:13.811 --> 35:15.646
Dude, that's like a nine or 10 footer.

35:15.646 --> 35:16.981
That is not like seven.

35:17.915 --> 35:19.183
That's huge!

35:19.183 --> 35:19.984
Oh geez.

35:19.984 --> 35:21.119
Do you see that?

35:22.120 --> 35:24.956
(water splashing)

35:30.428 --> 35:31.529
I don't know.

35:31.529 --> 35:32.663
He attacked us.

35:33.631 --> 35:35.133
He literally attacked us.

35:36.601 --> 35:39.337
- What you're dealing here is a very real possibility.

35:39.337 --> 35:40.505
- [Man] Watch out.

35:40.505 --> 35:41.873
Whoo. Oh my gosh.

35:44.842 --> 35:46.444
Oh, hold on.

35:47.845 --> 35:51.883
- I wonder, does the board at the Ocean Institute

35:51.949 --> 35:56.521
share your conviction on this bull shark theory?

35:57.688 --> 36:00.691
- It's not a theory, it's a fact.

36:00.725 --> 36:04.028
- I doubt they'd be very happy to have a major hit

36:04.028 --> 36:06.697
in their funding because one of their mad scientists

36:06.731 --> 36:11.736
was spouting erroneous rumors about sharks

36:12.503 --> 36:13.504
in freshwater lakes.

36:19.210 --> 36:21.012
- I'm sorry. What are you getting at?

36:23.347 --> 36:26.684
- We are very powerful people, Mr. Harper.

36:31.155 --> 36:32.356
Would you do me a favor?

36:33.224 --> 36:34.559
Would you give us the room?

36:38.663 --> 36:42.033
(Jacob Harper shuffling)

36:50.708 --> 36:53.211
(door closes)

36:59.250 --> 37:00.084
So.

37:02.620 --> 37:04.121
- Could be a problem.

37:04.188 --> 37:07.291
- I am not paying you to state the obvious.

37:07.291 --> 37:09.427
What do we have in place for this?

37:09.427 --> 37:11.095
- Containment.

37:11.095 --> 37:13.564
13 men have run against you.

37:13.598 --> 37:15.633
They all thought they had a chance.

37:15.633 --> 37:16.534
They lost.

37:17.868 --> 37:20.871
We didn't get here by forgetting how we pay our rent.

37:20.905 --> 37:24.976
- And now I'm running up against a fucking shark.

37:24.976 --> 37:27.144
- Don't twist my words.

37:27.211 --> 37:29.280
I'm not saying we win.

37:29.280 --> 37:33.618
I'm saying we take out the story's legs, then its heart.

37:34.986 --> 37:36.988
- And how do we do that?

37:38.823 --> 37:40.091
- (sighs) Who else knows?

37:41.459 --> 37:43.628
(tense music)

37:43.628 --> 37:45.396
- [Mayor] The game warden.

37:45.429 --> 37:46.897
- The alcoholic?

37:46.897 --> 37:48.299
- What's that matter?

37:48.299 --> 37:49.900
- He's the easiest to discredit.

37:51.602 --> 37:52.436
The sheriff?

37:53.604 --> 37:55.106
- He's not a problem. Trust me.

37:56.274 --> 37:58.075
He wants this quiet as much as I do.

37:59.810 --> 38:00.611
- Okay.

38:01.979 --> 38:05.483
We keep the victims' families quiet a little bit longer

38:05.483 --> 38:08.152
until we can draft something up on our side.

38:08.152 --> 38:11.689
Anyone talks, we know the weakest link.

38:11.756 --> 38:15.626
All we have to do is cut him loose and you look like a hero.

38:16.827 --> 38:19.964
- Okay.

38:19.964 --> 38:21.132
- All right then.

38:21.132 --> 38:23.434
The pieces are all on the board

38:23.434 --> 38:27.204
unless there's anyone else who knows about your problem?

38:27.204 --> 38:30.508
(tense music)

38:30.508 --> 38:31.342
- Mm.

38:33.177 --> 38:35.946
(paper rustling)

38:45.990 --> 38:49.160
(tense music)

38:49.193 --> 38:50.828
(door shuts)

38:50.828 --> 38:53.497
- Don't turn around, stay calm.

38:55.232 --> 38:57.168
This is simply two civil servants

38:57.201 --> 38:59.136
having a friendly conversation.

39:06.043 --> 39:08.546
There are so many kinds of bravery in this world.

39:10.381 --> 39:13.517
Sometimes, bravery means laying down your life

39:13.517 --> 39:16.987
for something bigger than yourself or for someone else.

39:16.987 --> 39:19.056
(Coroner Hamlin chomps on apple)

39:19.056 --> 39:23.394
Sometimes, it means giving up everything you've ever known,

39:23.394 --> 39:24.829
everything you've ever loved

39:26.530 --> 39:28.199
for the sake of something greater.

39:29.500 --> 39:30.568
Sometimes, it doesn't.

39:32.036 --> 39:36.273
Sometimes bravery simply means gritting your teeth

39:36.273 --> 39:41.278
through the pain, everyday work, slow walk to a better life,

39:43.047 --> 39:45.716
and doing what you're asked to do

39:47.084 --> 39:48.719
whether or not you agree with it.

39:53.391 --> 39:54.225
- Okay?

39:55.926 --> 39:56.727
Mr. Mayor.

39:58.095 --> 40:00.598
- I don't need you to say anything right now,

40:02.433 --> 40:04.635
but that last kind of bravery I talked about,

40:06.103 --> 40:08.572
that's the kind of bravery you're gonna need right now.

40:12.410 --> 40:14.879
(door opens)

40:14.879 --> 40:16.313
We'll be in touch.

40:16.313 --> 40:18.082
Y'all enjoy the rest of your lunch.

40:21.886 --> 40:24.288
(door shuts)

40:27.091 --> 40:30.327
(keys jingle)

40:30.327 --> 40:32.930
(car rumbling)

40:40.638 --> 40:43.507
(leaves crunching)

40:46.143 --> 40:48.245
(paper rustles)

40:48.279 --> 40:50.981
(birds chirping)

40:58.956 --> 41:03.627
(phone buzzes) - This is Hamlin.

41:03.661 --> 41:05.496
- [Sheriff] Don't think, just listen.

41:06.931 --> 41:08.132
You're gonna go back to your office this afternoon,

41:08.165 --> 41:10.267
and you're gonna file that dead girl's report.

41:11.469 --> 41:13.704
Only difference is, this time, when you file it,

41:15.206 --> 41:17.308
you're gonna leave the cause of death blank.

41:18.642 --> 41:19.477
Understood?

41:22.546 --> 41:23.380
Hamlin.

41:25.616 --> 41:29.487
- Yes, I understand. (sighs)

41:30.488 --> 41:31.322
Fuck.

41:34.024 --> 41:39.029
(tense music) (water warbling)

41:41.799 --> 41:44.001
(birds chirping)

41:44.034 --> 41:48.539
(children laughing) (children yelling)

41:48.539 --> 41:50.574
(water splashing)

41:50.574 --> 41:55.546
(tense music) (water warbling)

41:58.549 --> 42:01.385
(children laughing) (children yelling)

42:01.385 --> 42:04.088
(birds chirping)

42:06.223 --> 42:11.228
(ducks quacking) (tense music)

42:19.603 --> 42:22.439
(water splashing)

42:35.085 --> 42:40.090
(dog panting) (water splashing)

42:49.433 --> 42:51.902
(tense music)

42:55.039 --> 42:57.875
(person whistling)

43:00.044 --> 43:03.113
(dog panting)

43:03.113 --> 43:05.616
(tense music)

43:10.621 --> 43:14.892
(dog barks) (dog whimpering)

43:14.892 --> 43:17.728
(water splashing)

43:28.138 --> 43:30.641
(tense music)

43:47.024 --> 43:49.193
(Spencer coughs) (Spencer spits)

43:49.259 --> 43:50.027
- You're late.

43:53.030 --> 43:55.032
Have you even slept? You look like shit.

43:57.267 --> 44:00.270
- It's a bull shark. We need to close the lake down.

44:00.270 --> 44:02.606
- Bull shark? What makes you so sure?

44:03.707 --> 44:04.541
- Did you hear what I just said?

44:04.608 --> 44:05.809
- I heard you.

44:05.843 --> 44:06.810
But close down the lake?

44:06.810 --> 44:08.479
With the tourists coming in?

44:10.014 --> 44:12.149
You can't just wash those tax dollars away.

44:12.149 --> 44:14.485
I'm up for reelection in two and a half months.

44:15.686 --> 44:17.287
Can't handle that kind of action.

44:17.287 --> 44:19.123
- No, what you can't handle, Wilson,

44:19.123 --> 44:21.392
is a kid getting eaten by a shark.

44:21.392 --> 44:22.292
Can't afford that.

44:23.494 --> 44:24.995
- What are you not telling me?

44:26.330 --> 44:28.632
- The guy at the Ocean Institute, I went and saw him.

44:30.367 --> 44:32.036
Good news is mother sharks don't allow their young

44:32.036 --> 44:33.070
to hunt on their own.

44:34.538 --> 44:37.975
That, plus the size of the bite radius on the dead girl

44:39.176 --> 44:40.744
says we're looking at one shark, not two.

44:42.713 --> 44:45.215
- So what happened to the mother shark?

44:45.215 --> 44:47.518
- His best guess? Didn't survive the birth.

44:49.053 --> 44:51.722
So we've got one dead shark under water

44:51.722 --> 44:54.058
and another one looking for more meals

44:54.058 --> 44:55.225
and it's fucking hungry.

44:56.694 --> 44:58.362
- Did you run this past the mayor?

44:59.763 --> 45:01.198
- Just got in, Pete.

45:01.231 --> 45:02.266
First face I've seen.

45:04.068 --> 45:05.536
We need divers to confirm it.

45:06.704 --> 45:08.272
Otherwise, we trust the expert and assume

45:08.272 --> 45:11.275
if the shark is feeding, that it's got no other choice.

45:11.275 --> 45:12.109
Mother's dead.

45:15.412 --> 45:17.414
- We need to get on the boat.

45:17.448 --> 45:19.283
I can't keep that little girl's mother quiet much longer.

45:19.349 --> 45:21.118
- No, what you need to do is shut down the damn lake.

45:21.118 --> 45:22.619
Cut off its food supply.

45:22.686 --> 45:25.255
- We don't have to do that if we kill the damn thing first.

45:25.255 --> 45:26.957
Now I'm still the fucking sheriff in this town.

45:27.024 --> 45:28.959
Last time I checked, you answer to me.

45:31.795 --> 45:32.596
- Right.

45:33.864 --> 45:35.466
- All right.

45:35.466 --> 45:37.801
So go find us a boat and we'll go out there

45:37.801 --> 45:39.636
and kill this fucking thing.

45:39.636 --> 45:42.306
But we're gonna be real quiet about it, right?

45:43.741 --> 45:46.410
Nobody's gotta know about this but us.

45:46.443 --> 45:47.611
In the meantime, we'll stick

45:47.611 --> 45:49.446
with the whole water testing story.

45:51.115 --> 45:54.218
Hey, I do not want mass hysteria.

45:55.385 --> 45:57.054
You got me?

45:57.054 --> 45:58.055
- I got you.

